site: Villages near mangroves - Affiniam, Diagobel, Tendimane
assi: "177 An. gambiae s.l. identified from the mangrove sites by cyto. 91% An. gambiae s.s., 5% An. melas, 4% An. arabiensis. At the freshwater sites 100% of 52 specimens were An. gambiae s.s. Additional samples were taken from the mangrove sites by larvae , MB and LT. Of these, 2128/2733 were freshwater species of An. gambiae s.l. and the remainder An. melas by palpal ratio."
citation: Faye, O., Gaye, O., Faye, O. and Diallo, S. (1994).  [Transmission of malaria in villages far away or situated on the border of a mangrove in Senegal]. Bulletin de la Socit de Pathologie Exotique, 87(3):157-63

assi: "A random sample of 224 (from 1479 captured during MBI and MBO) of An. gambiae complex females were id-ed using PCR. An arabiensis and An gambiae wre found present with An gambiae ss predominanting at a frequency of 84.9%. From HRI, 134/430 were tested and An gambiae ss also predominated from these (92.5%). A sample of An gambiae ss were tested by PCR for molecular forms and only the S form was found. A sample of 50 An nili complex were also tested by PCR to id siblings and all were found to be An nili ss. Data is presented as given in article."
citation: Dia, I., Diop, T., Rakotoarivony, I., Kengne, P. and Fontenille, D. (2003).  Bionomics of Anopheles gambiae Giles, An. arabiensis Patton, An. funestus Giles and An. nili (Theobald) (Diptera: Culicidae) and transmission of Plasmodium falciparum in a Sudano-Guinean zone (Ngari, Senegal). Journal of Medical Entomology, 40(3):279-83

assi: "A random sample of 224 (from 1479 captured during MBI and MBO) of An. gambiae complex females were id-ed using PCR. An arabiensis and An gambiae wre found present with An gambiae ss predominanting at a frequency of 84.9%. From HRI, 134/430 were tested and An gambiae ss also predominated from these (92.5%). A sample of An gambiae ss were tested by PCR for molecular forms and only the S form was found. A sample of 50 An nili complex were also tested by PCR to id siblings and all were found to be An nili ss. Data is presented as given in article."

assi: "All An. gambiae s.l. caught before Sep 2005 (373), a random sample from Sep - Dec 2005 (346), a random sample from Sep - Oct 2006 (137) and all CSP positive specimens were identified. In 2005, 97.8% An. arabiensis, 2.0% An. melas, 0.2% An. gambiae s.s. M form. In 2006, 98.5% An. arabiensis, 1.5% An. gambiae s.s. M form."
citation: Pags, F., Texier, G., Pradines, B., Gadiaga, L., Machault, V., Jarjaval, F., Penhoat, K., Berger, F., Trape, J.F., Rogier, C. and Sokhna, C. (2008).  Malaria transmission in Dakar: a two-year survey. Malaria Journal, 7:178

assi: "All An. gambiae s.l. caught before Sep 2005 (82), a random sample from Sep - Dec 2005 (216), a random sample from Sep - Oct 2006 (134) and all CSP positive specimens were identified. In 2005, 100% An. arabiensis. In 2006, all An. arabiensis except for one specimen of An. melas"
